---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const vCode = `fn main() {
    words := ['hello', 'world', 'v']
    for w in words {
        println(w.to_upper())
    }
}`;
---
<Base title="Tyra vs V" description="Comparing Tyra and V for LLM code generation — different goals, different tradeoffs">
  <style>
    .compare-header { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .compare-header p { color: var(--text-muted); max-width: 680px; }
    .rate-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    @media (max-width: 600px) { .rate-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
    .rate-card { background: var(--bg-secondary); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .rate-card.tyra { border-color: var(--accent); }
    .rate-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 700; }
    .rate-card.tyra .rate-value { color: var(--accent); }
    .rate-lang { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 0.25rem; }
    .rate-note { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 0.5rem; }
    .side-by-side { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    @media (max-width: 700px) { .side-by-side { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
    .code-block-label { font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-muted); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
    .tradeoff-list { color: var(--text-muted); padding-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.925rem; }
    .tradeoff-list li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; line-height: 1.7; }
    .honest-note { background: var(--bg-secondary); border-left: 3px solid var(--border); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0; color: var(--text-muted); font-size: 0.875rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
  </style>

  <div class="compare-header">
    <h1>Tyra vs V</h1>
    <p>
      V (vlang) is a systems programming language aimed at simplicity, performance, and safety.
      It occupies a different niche from Tyra — low-level systems work vs. web backends and CLI tools.
      This comparison focuses on LLM generation accuracy, where the two languages have different results.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="rate-grid">
    <div class="rate-card">
      <div class="rate-value">49.0%</div>
      <div class="rate-lang">V</div>
      <div class="rate-note">Single seed estimate</div>
    </div>
    <div class="rate-card tyra">
      <div class="rate-value">88.7%</div>
      <div class="rate-lang">Tyra + spec</div>
      <div class="rate-note">Multi-seed mean (3 seeds), spec injected</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    V's 49% likely reflects limited LLM training data — V is a newer language with a smaller
    corpus of public code. Tyra has the same problem (zero training data), but compensates with
    spec injection. The comparison illustrates that spec injection can be more effective than
    relying on incidental training data for new languages.
  </p>

  <h2>Side-by-side: string manipulation</h2>

  <div class="side-by-side">
    <div>
      <div class="code-block-label">Tyra</div>
      <pre><code>{`import string

fn main() -> Unit
  let words = ["hello", "world", "tyra"]
  for w in words
    println(string.to_upper(w))
  end
end`}</code></pre>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="code-block-label">V</div>
      <pre><code>{vCode}</code></pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    V uses method syntax for string operations; Tyra uses module functions. Both are readable.
    V's single-quote string literals and curly brace blocks are syntactic conventions that differ
    from the majority of LLM training data, which may contribute to generation errors.
  </p>

  <h2>Different goals</h2>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    V is designed for systems programming — manual memory management (optional), C interop,
    no garbage collector, fast compilation to small binaries. Tyra is designed for
    web backends and CLI tools where managed memory and high-level abstractions matter more.
    These are complementary tools for different problem domains.
  </p>

  <h2>Honest tradeoffs</h2>

  <ul class="tradeoff-list">
    <li><strong>V wins:</strong> Systems-level control, C interop, and manual memory management when needed. Tyra has none of these.</li>
    <li><strong>V wins:</strong> Produces small, fast binaries suitable for embedded or constrained environments.</li>
    <li><strong>V wins:</strong> No garbage collector — predictable latency in performance-critical code.</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra advantage:</strong> Spec-injected LLM generation at 88.7% vs. V's 49% — significantly better first-try accuracy for application-level code.</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra advantage:</strong> Higher-level abstractions (map, set, json stdlib) with a clean module system.</li>
    <li><strong>Tyra is new:</strong> Smaller community, less tooling, no production track record.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="honest-note">
    V and Tyra target different use cases. If you need systems-level control, V is the better fit.
    If you're building web APIs or CLI tools with LLM-generated code, Tyra's spec injection gives
    a meaningful accuracy advantage.
  </div>

  <p style="color: var(--text-muted);">
    <a href="/leaderboard">View full leaderboard &rarr;</a>
  </p>
</Base>
